A3: SPL Library Checkouts

Introduction

I chose to analyze the dataset that contained information about items checked out at least 10 times a month from 2017 - 2023. I thought this would be really interesting to look at to see what books have been popular within the Seattle population for a longer period of time. By understanding this information, I can better illustrate which types of media and of which subject category are most popular within people living in this area. This information can be utilized in the future to better inform what types of products the library invests in and how to improve the products and services based on what people typically enjoy.

Summary Information

Overall, this dataset has 816354 items checked out including ebooks, books, magazines, movies, and comics, to name a few. The most common method of checking out was by using OverDrive, a library company that digitally distributes ebooks, audiobooks, and online magazines. Over the course of 2017 - 2023, the item that was checked out the most number of times was So You Want to Talk about Race (Unabridged) by Ijeoma Oluo. This is a non - fiction book published in 2018 that discusses race in contemporary America. Considering the vast amounts of protests related to police brutality and Black Lives Matter that began in 2020, I believe that this makes sense. In relation, the genre of the most commonly checked out item, the category that had the most number of items checked out within it is African American Nonfiction, Nonfiction, Politics, Sociology. In addition, the publisher that made the most number of checked out items was Blackstone Audio, Inc., which was founded in 2007 and purchased by Hasbro in 2019. Finally, in 2017 the most common type of media checkout was MIXED, which is the same as 2023, as the most common type of media checkout was also MIXED.

The Dataset

This data is collected by the Seattle Public Library, the public library system serving Seattle, Washington that was founded in 1890. This dataset includes information about items checked out at least 10 times per month from 2017 - 2023. The checkout items include items like ebooks, books, magazines, movies, CDs, television dics, and audiobooks, though this is not an exhaustive list. This data was collected through the Open Data program generated by the City of Seattle. This program aims to provide open access to data with the hope of improving the quality of life for residents, promoting economic development and enrichment, and to identify opportunities to better serve the public. When looking at this data, I do not believe that there are any ethical questions that need to be addressed. However, I think it is important to think critically when it comes to implementing the conclusions that are generated using this data. When utilizing this data and the conclusions, it is important to think about how library resources are utilized by different groups of people, and implement policies and products that continue to be equitable to all Seattle residents. Finally, the possible limitations that come with this data include the inability to see at what point in the month people checked out items, whether that be at the beginning, middle, or end of the month.

First Trends Over Time Chart

I chose to look at trends of how the total number of reading items checked out from the Seattle Public Library has changed over time. I was interested in this because I was curious to see if the number of book checkouts decreased when the pandemic began and people had less access to the physical products from the library. In addition, I wanted to see if the number of ebooks and audiobooks that were checked out increased, as these would be accessible to people from home. The graph shows that this is true, as there is a sharp decline in the number of book checkouts from 2019 to 2020, and then a slight increase and subsequent decrease after. Opposingly, the number of ebook and audiobook checkouts increased from 2017 to 2022, before decreasing into 2023. However, the decline that is seen into 2023 in all 3 categories is likely because 2023 has just begun, so there is an uneven comparison between a whole year of checkouts from 2022 vs.only two months of checkout data in 2023.

Second Trends Over Time Chart

I was interested in looking at the total number of checkouts per item type, in order to determine what the most popular type of checkout item is. Not surprisingly, this graph shows that the most checked out item from the library is physical books, followed closely by audiobooks. Next, comic books and CR (what I believe to mean community room) are the next group of most checked out, followed by atlas/maps. For this chart, I created a bar chart with a zoom in on the columns that were smaller, Atlas, CR, and Comics, since they could not properly be viewed on the right bar chart.

Your Choice

For my last graph, I was curious to see what the top 10 most checked out books were from the library, because I really enjoy reading and was interested to see what types of books are most popular within the Seattle area. The most checked out book was The Midnight Line by Lee Child. This was checked out almost 2 times more than the 2nd highest most checked out book. Interestingly, the rest of the most checked out books were checked out roughly the same amount of times, about 750 times from 2017 - 2023. Many of these books relate to politics and the current culture, seen by Becoming, Fear: Trump in the White House, and Fire and Fury: Inside the Trump White House. Most of these are also non - fiction books, with less fiction books. This may indicate that it tends to be older adults checking out books from the library, as opposed to younger children.
